org.spf4j.base

Enum SysExits

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<SysExits>
      • org.spf4j.base.SysExits
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<SysExits>

    public enum SysExits
extends Enum<SysExits>
    some "standard" process exit codes from: http://tldp.org/LDP/abs/html/index.html https://www.freebsd.org/cgi/man.cgi?query=sysexits&apropos=0&sektion=0&manpath=FreeBSD+4.3-RELEASE&format=html http://journal.thobe.org/2013/02/jvms-and-kill-signals.html
    Author:
    zoly

      • OK

        public static final SysExits OK
        Everything is OK.

      • EX_GENERAL

        public static final SysExits EX_GENERAL
        Catch all for general errors.

      • EX_SHELL_BUILTIN_MISSUSE

        public static final SysExits EX_SHELL_BUILTIN_MISSUSE
        Shell build in miss-use.

      • EX_USAGE

        public static final SysExits EX_USAGE
        The command was used incorrectly, e.g., with the wrong number of arguments, a bad flag, a bad syntax in a parameter, or whatever.

      • EX_DATAERR

        public static final SysExits EX_DATAERR
        The input data was incorrect in some way. This should only be used for user's data and not system files.

      • EX_NOINPUT

        public static final SysExits EX_NOINPUT
        An input file (not a system file) did not exist or was not readable. This could also include errors like ``No message'' to a mailer (if it cared to catch it).

      • EX_NOUSER

        public static final SysExits EX_NOUSER
        The user specified did not exist. This might be used for mail addresses or remote logins.

      • EX_NOHOST

        public static final SysExits EX_NOHOST
        The host specified did not exist. This is used in mail addresses or network requests.

      • EX_UNAVAILABLE

        public static final SysExits EX_UNAVAILABLE
        A service is unavailable. This can occur if a support program or file does not exist. This can also be used as a catchall message when something you wanted to do doesn't work, but you don't know why.

      • EX_SOFTWARE

        public static final SysExits EX_SOFTWARE
        An internal software error has been detected. This should be limited to non-operating system related errors as possible.

      • EX_OSERR

        public static final SysExits EX_OSERR
        An operating system error has been detected. This is intended to be used for such things as ``cannot fork'', ``cannot create pipe'', or the like. It includes things like getuid returning a user that does not exist in the passwd file.

      • EX_OSFILE

        public static final SysExits EX_OSFILE
        Some system file (e.g., /etc/passwd, /var/run/utmp,etc.) does not exist, cannot be opened, or has some sort of error (e.g., syntax error).

      • EX_CANTCREAT

        public static final SysExits EX_CANTCREAT
        A (user specified) output file cannot be created.

      • EX_IOERR

        public static final SysExits EX_IOERR
        An error occurred while doing I/O on some file.

      • EX_TEMPFAIL

        public static final SysExits EX_TEMPFAIL
        Temporary failure, indicating something that is not really an error. In sendmail, this means that a mailer (e.g.) could not create a connection, and the request should be reattempted later.

      • EX_PROTOCOL

        public static final SysExits EX_PROTOCOL
        The remote system returned something that was ``not possible'' during a protocol exchange.

      • EX_NOPERM

        public static final SysExits EX_NOPERM
        You did not have sufficient permission to perform the operation. This is not intended for file system problems, which should use EX_NOINPUT or EX_CANTCREAT, but rather for higher level permissions.

      • EX_CONFIG

        public static final SysExits EX_CONFIG
        Something was found in an unconfigured or misconfigured state.

        public static final SysExits EX_SIG_HUP
        Section caused by exit due to signal. where signal name is same on Linux, Solaris and MacOS enum has the appropriate name. for linux see: http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/signal.7.html or run man signal on you OS of choice.
